Code used for the simulation
----------------------------

We start by loading the Eskdalemuir data, which we have already used
this weeek, and plot the time series again.

    load("../../data/week2/esktem.RData")
    plot(esktem, main="Temperatures in Eskdalemuir", col=2)

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width=".45\textwidth" />

Next, we have to construct the covariate matrix containing the linear
trend and the harmonic terms for the seasonal effect.

    t <- seq(1914, length=length(esktem), by=1/12)
    xreg <- cbind(t, sin(2*pi*t), cos(2*pi*t))

We can now use the function `auto.arima` to search for the best model.

    library(forecast)
    model <- auto.arima(esktem, seasonal=FALSE, xreg=xreg)
    summary(model)

    ## Series: esktem 
    ## Regression with ARIMA(2,0,2) errors

Next we plot the linear trend and overlay the partial residuals (i.e. we
remove the estimated seasonal effect from the temperatures to obtain
what is effectively a temperature anomaly).

    beta <- coef(model)[5:8]
    plot(t, esktem-beta[3]*sin(2*pi*t) - beta[4]*cos(2*pi*t), col=3, xlab="Year", ylab="Long-term trend")
    title("Long-term trend")
    abline(beta[1], beta[2], lwd=2, col=2)

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width=".45\textwidth" />

Finally we plot the seasonal effect and overlay the partial residuals
(this time ew remove the long-term trend).

    plot(t%%1, esktem-beta[1]-beta[2]*t, xaxt="n", xlab="Month", ylab="Seasonal effect", col=3)
    title("Seasonal effect")
    axis(side=1, at=0:11/12,labels=c("Jan","Feb","Mar","Apr","May", "Jun", "Jul", "Aug","Sep","Oct", "Nov","Dec"))
    tt <- seq(0,1,len=1e4)
    lines(tt, beta[3]*sin(2*pi*tt) + beta[4]*cos(2*pi*tt), lwd=2, col=2)
